                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.011/409½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Chief of the Division of
                        the American Republics</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Duggan</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-28">May 28,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Cuban Ambassador telephoned me at about six o’clock to say that he had spoken
                    on the telephone with his brother who confirmed that there had been a tussle in
                    the Constituent Assembly yesterday regarding the mortgage moratorium. His
                    brother was going to the Coordinating Committee then and would convey to Senator
                    Casanova the views of the Department. The Ambassador said that he took the
                    liberty of stating that these views were those held by Mr. Welles, in order that
                    the message to Senator Casanova might be of a more personal nature.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador stated that he might hear further from his brother after the
                    latter spoke with Casanova; in any case he felt that he was doing all that he
                    could to bring about a moderate solution.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
